snippet.textDisplay:
I had to sell my NB Miata 12years ago to get my VIPER. Back then I always thought of the MIATA as a learning tool & stepping stone to be able to successfully pilot my future VIPER. This is because they share the same driving platform(front engine, RWD, 50/50weight) with similar handling dynamics. The VIPER is a MIATA on steroids, and it is best to thoroughly understand the handling dynamics prior to introducing all that power.

Love the VIPER, but I always missed the nimbleness and daily drivability of the MIATA. Loved the 2016 Miata "ND" Platform but was turned off from its economy-oriented motor being a direct hand-me-down from the Mazda3, and the unreliable transmission.
When the 2019 ND2's revised motor was introduced I was BLOWN AWAY. Mazda finally gave their sportscar a PROPER race motor by revising nearly every internal component which resulted in a significantly higher redline & power increase from 155 to 181. I had to have one, so i sold my dailydriver(2012 AudiTT) and grabbed a new sport model for $24K which I thought was very reasonable for what it is.

Now i have TWO DREAM CARS :-)

snippet.textDisplay: Nice to see more people agreeing on importance of good tires. Though i don't think that RE71 were right choice. For street imho one is better off with Michelin PS4S/Goodyear E F1 SS/Conti SC6.
